Question 4 U dataset: MOISSANITE

  1. Calculate the regression residuals.
  2. Plot the residuals against x. Do you detect a trend?
  3. Propose an alternative model based on the plot, part b.
  4. Fit and analyze the model you proposed in part c.
setwd("~/Documents/SFSU.FALL.2017/424/R/R/Exercises&Examples")
load("MOISSANITE.Rdata")
View(MOISSANITE)
  1. calculate residuals
model = lm(MOISSANITE$VOLUME~MOISSANITE$PRESSURE)
plot(model, which = 1:1)

residuals(model)
##           1           2           3           4           5           6 
##  1.38508113 -0.21233184 -0.77652790 -0.64485018 -0.28219329 -0.42754316 
##           7           8           9          10          11 
## -0.22624964  0.04630246  0.28528837  0.28528837  0.56773568
sum(residuals(model))
## [1] -1.554312e-15

After plotting the residuals of the model, the plot of FItted values vs Residuals, we can see that there is a trend in the residuals and instead of being linear, appears to be quadratic.

The new proposed model is \(E(y)=\hat\beta_0 + \hat\beta_1x_1 + \hat\beta_2x_1^2\) Testing this:

model2 = lm(MOISSANITE$VOLUME~MOISSANITE$PRESSURE+I(MOISSANITE$PRESSURE^2))
plot(model2,which = 1:1)

Which we can see that the residuals are within 2s and appear to be far more randomnly distributed than the purely linear model.

Question 11

E(y) = 0 + 1 x 1 + 2 x 2 + 3 x 1 x 2 . Fit the model to the data saved in the GASTURBINE file, then plot the residuals against predicted heat rate. Is the assumption of a constant error variance reasonably satisfied? If not, suggest how to modify the model.

load("GASTURBINE.Rdata")
View(GASTURBINE)
heatrate= GASTURBINE$HEATRATE
rpm = GASTURBINE$RPM
cpratio = GASTURBINE$CPRATIO
model = lm(heatrate~cpratio+rpm+I(cpratio*rpm))
summary(model)

since we see that the distribution is roughly binomial, we can try the transformation \(sin^{-1}\sqrt{y}\). Further investigation concludes that the constant error variation seems to be satisfied.

Quesstion 20

The Normal Q-Q plot is displayed below. The chart compares the standardized residuals with the quartiles that should be theoretically exist.

model = lm(heatrate~cpratio+rpm+I(cpratio*rpm))
plot(model, which = 2:2)

Here, we graph the residuals versus the expected residuals under the assumption of normality. If we assume normality, then we expect to see a near straight line from plotting th two against eachother. Failing to see this would be akin to a proof by contradiction. We assume the plot will be a straight line and see if the shows us otherwise. In this case, excluding the 3 extreme outliers, 11,36,64, this can be viewed as sufficiently normal.

GASTURBINE
trimmedData = GASTURBINE[-11,]
model = lm(trimmedData$HEATRATE~trimmedData$CPRATIO+trimmedData$RPM+I(trimmedData$CPRATIO*trimmedData$RPM), data = trimmedData)
plot(model, which = 2:2)

trimmedData = GASTURBINE[c(-11,-36),]
model = lm(trimmedData$HEATRATE~trimmedData$CPRATIO+trimmedData$RPM+I(trimmedData$CPRATIO*trimmedData$RPM), data = trimmedData)
plot(model, which = 2:2)

trimmedData = GASTURBINE[c(-11,-36, -64),]
model = lm(trimmedData$HEATRATE~trimmedData$CPRATIO+trimmedData$RPM+I(trimmedData$CPRATIO*trimmedData$RPM), data = trimmedData)
plot(model, which = 2:2)
